1 Data visualization: five named graphs

1.1 Learning objectives

  1. You familiar with the major visualization strategies for univariate, bivariate, and multivariate plots.

  2. You can identify the appropriate plot(s) for visualizing discrete variables, continuous variables, and a combinations of both.

  3. You can explain the names, functions, and types of variables used by each of the five named graphs (5NG) .

1.2 Five named graphs - the 5NG

In order to keep things simple in this chapter, we will cover some of the more basic geom_ functions. We will primarily focus on five different types of graphics, each with a commonly given name. We term these âfive named graphsâ or in abbreviated form, the 5NG:

  1. scatterplots
  2. linegraphs
  3. histograms
  4. boxplots
  5. barplots

Weâll also present some variations of these plots, but with this basic repertoire of five graphics in your toolbox, you can visualize a wide array of different variable types. Note that certain plots are only appropriate for discrete variables, while others are only appropriate for continuous variables.

1.3 Univariate graphs

Univariate graphs plot the distribution of data from a single variable. The variable can be discrete (e.g., race, sex) or continuous (e.g., age, weight).

1.3.1 Discrete

The distribution of a single discrete variable is typically plotted with a barplot, or (less commonly) a pie chart.

1.3.2 Continuous

The distribution of a single continuous variable is typically plotted with a histogram or a kernel density plot.

1.4 Bivariate graphs

Bivariate graphs display the relationship between two variables. The type of graph will depend on the measurement level of the variables (discrete or continuous).

1.4.1 Continuous vs.Â continuous

The relationship between two continuous variables is typically displayed using scatterplots and linegraphs.

The simplest display of two continuous variables is a scatterplot, with each variable represented on an axis.

It is often useful to summarize the relationship displayed in the scatterplot using a best fit line. Many types of lines are supported, including linear, polynomial, and nonparametric (loess).

When one of the two variables represents time, a linegraph can be an effective method of displaying relationship.

For example, we van use a linegraph to visualize time series data such as disease incidence per epidemic week.

1.4.2 Discrete vs.Â Continuous

When plotting the relationship between a discrete variable and a continuous variable, a large number of graph types are available. These include barplots, column charts, side-by-side boxplots, side-by-side violin plots, ridgeline plots, and more.

A side-by-side boxplot is very useful for comparing distributions of between groups of a continuous variable. The continuous variable is grouped by the levels of a discrete variable.

1.5 Multivariate Graphs

Multivariate graphs display the relationships among three or more variables. There are two common methods for accommodating multiple variables: grouping and faceting.

1.5.1 Grouping

In grouping, the values of the first two variables are mapped to the x and y axes. Then additional variables are mapped to other visual characteristics such as color, shape, size, line type, and transparency. Grouping allows you to plot the data for multiple groups in a single graph.

For example, the scatterplot illustration above, the color of the points could represent a third discrete variable. There are four different colors one for each level of the third variable.

1.5.2 Faceting

In faceting, a graph consists of several separate plots or small multiples, one for each level of a third variable

Grouping and faceting can turn bivariate graphs into multivariate graphs. Grouping allows you to plot multiple variables in a single graph, using visual characteristics such as color, shape, and size. When we facet graphs, we split a graph up into multiple plotting panels, where each panel contains a subset of the data.

1.6 5NG summary table

Letâs recap all five of the five named graphs (5NG) in a table summarizing their differences. Using these 5NG, youâll be able to visualize the distributions and relationships of variables contained in a wide array of datasets. This will be even more the case as we start to map more variables to more of each geometric objectâs aesthetic attribute options, further unlocking the awesome power of the ggplot2 package.

Summary of Five Named Graphs
Name Graph Shows geom_*() function Notes
1 Scatterplot Relationship between 2 continuous variables geom_point() A best fit line can summarize the relationship displayed in the scatterplot, using geom_smooth()
2 Linegraph Relationship between 2 continuous variables geom_line() Used when there is a sequential order to x-variable (e.g., time)
3 Histogram Distribution of 1 continuous variable geom_histogram() Facetted histograms show the distribution of 1 continuous variable split by the values of another discrete variable
4 Boxplot Distribution of 1 continuous variable split by the values of a discrete variable geom_boxplot() Violin plots with geom_violin() allow for a more precise representation of the distribution
5 Barplot Distribution of 1 discrete variable geom_bar() or geom_col() Stacked, side-by-side, and faceted barplots show the joint distribution of 2 discrete variables
